definition.value: A deficiency in the expression of the CD40 ligand on the surface of activated T-lymphocytes.
A deviation from the normal level of major histocompatibility complex class II molecules expressed at the cell surface.
A reduction from the normal level of major histocompatibility complex class II molecules expressed at the cell surface.
An increase above the normal level of major histocompatibility complex class II molecules expressed at the cell surface.

label.value: Abnormal proportion of CD4-positive T cells

definition.value: Any abnormality in the proportion of CD4-positive T cells relative to the total number of T cells.

label.value: Abnormal proportion of CD8-positive T cells

definition.value: Any abnormality in the proportion of CD8 T cells relative to the total number of T cells.

label.value: Abnormal proportion of naive T cells
Decreased proportion of naive T cells
Increased proportion of naive T cells
Abnormal proportion of double-negative alpha-beta regulatory T cell
Reduced proportion of CD4-negative, CD8-negative, alpha-beta regulatory T cells

definition.value: An abnormally decreased proportion of CD4-negative, CD8-negative (double negative or DN) alpha-beta regulatory T cells (Tregs) as compared to total number of T cells.
Impaired proliferation and expansion of a T cell population following activation by an antigenic stimulus.

An impaired immune response mediated by cells expressing specific receptors for antigen produced through a somatic diversification process, and allowing for an enhanced secondary response to subsequent exposures to the same antigen (immunological memory).

Any abnormality in the series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of a cytokine to a receptor on the surface of a cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

A defect or impairment in the series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of a cytokine to a receptor on the surface of a cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

label.value: Increased proportion of CD25+ mast cells

definition.value: Any anomaly of lymphocyte function.

label.value: Abnormal distribution of CD56 bright/dim natural killer cells

definition.value: Any structural anomaly of a chromosome, which is a thread like molecule consisting of DNA and proteins (chromatin) that contains DNA sequences for genes and other genetic elements in linear order.

An abnormal reduction in telomere length. Telomeres are non-coding, repetitive sequences of DNA at the ends of the chromosomes of eukaryotic cells which become shorter as cells divide, and when telomere attrition reaches its limit, cell proliferation arrest, senescence, and apoptosis can occur.
Any deviation from the normal quantity of secretion of nasal mucus, a thick viscous liquid produced by the mucous membranes of the nose.
Increased discharge of mucus from the nose.

label.value: Small yellow foveal lesion with surrounding gray zone

definition.value: Any structural anomaly of the cortex of the cerebellum.
The presence of a population of T cells with a restricted T cell receptor (TCR) repertoire derived from a limited number of TCR clones.
Repetition of sounds with no meaning.

label.value: Restricted or repetitive behaviors or interests

definition.value: A broad range of compulsive behaviors are repeated, including simple motor stereotypies and tics, as well as more complex repetitive movements or compulsions.

Prosody refers to the patterns of rhythm, stress, and intonation in spoken language. Abnormal prosody refers to abnormalities in the patterns of rhythm, stress, or intonation of speech or vocalization that can be heard by the observer. In general, this refers to overt and clear deviations in patterns from culturally accepted norms but many also include differences noted in comparison to the usual patterns of the individual (a quiet person suddenly becomes loud or vice versa).

A speech pattern characterized by a persistently abnormal lack of tone in the voice. Monotonic speech is typically ongoing, lasting throughout the day, but may have a diurnal variation in the pattern, i.e. slower at specific times of the day.
